of like, where are you spending your time?
The way I like to phrase this, what are you willing to say no to?
Are we selling products or are we building a brand?
And we're not doing this just to sell product.
We're really trying to create a brand that's going to last.
And in order to do that, we've got to be able to focus.
And if winter is where we go, then we're going to have to liquidate a lot of this summer
stuff and really lean into who we really are.
And there's plenty of brands out there who are successful in focusing on a particular
season.
So I don't think we need to do for four quarters a year, even though our brains are wired to
wanting to win every single month, every single quarter.
But that's sometimes how you lose.
Are we your target audience?
You know us pretty well.
Do we fit within the boundaries of who you're trying to connect with?
That you for sure are part of the target audience.
I mean.
So what's wrong with Destin?
No, it's a serious question though.
That's it is a serious question.
Yeah.
Well, just on opportunity to mock you.
Just for fun, the name for Muscox actually means animal with skin like a beard.
So I think Destin being clean shaven, you know, that's why there's no beard there.
It's just a decision that Destin makes to shave the beard that would otherwise flourish.
I see the joke, but I also there's some seriousness here and I think that's interesting.
Like the mountain man kind of feel is part of what you're going for.
My brand would be more of a soft nerdy type, right?
Look, at the end of the day, I don't think this is a hot take to say we're happy for
anyone to buy our products, but all customers were not created equal.
And we want to create products that people are going to really love that are in that
narrow lane of the rugged outdoorsman.
And regardless of how often you actually do get outside and to experience those things,
someone who has that self identity as someone who appreciates and loves to be outdoors and
to pursue adventure outdoors.
That's really who our target market is.
So right now, I am enormously brand loyal to Obaz shoes to I don't even I've never
known if I say it right.
I assume it's not oboes because that sounds weird, but that's what I buy.
I buy Prana pants and that's pretty much it.
Save some Mac weld and I bought because you guys got me connected with them and I like
their stuff for my lounge around pants.
And I wear a bunch of Kavu flannels, real heavy flannels, some cool occasionally I'll
do a Columbia or North Face, but usually more in that exclusively outdoor store kind of
range in terms of tops, pullovers, things like that.
So what you're telling me is that you would like to displace one or more of those brands
to be in my short rotation of stuff that I buy someone like me and have me not just
be like, oh, yeah, that's cool.
I would wear that one.
But instead, I can't wait to see what MuscoX comes up with this year.
It always works.
It never goes wrong.
Customer service is great.
I like the story it tells.
I am willing to marry my personal brand as a guy who likes the outside to MuscoX.
Is that what I'm hearing?
You nailed it.
Now we are David and we got a slingshot and we're trying to shoot it.
Do you feel like you have to slay the Goliath in order to win or do you feel like you have
to just survive and find a niche market?
No, I think it's more the latter.
I mean, the big guys, they're not going anywhere.
Thank you.
I like them.
Yeah, they do good work.
There's nothing wrong with that.
And we think there's an opportunity to continue to modernize as a brand, not modernize again,
from the perspective of being the most trendy.
But we're a new modern brand that tries to understand men and their desire to seek out
outdoor adventure and to put together quality stuff that makes their adventure easier and
has thoughtful features along the way.
I Googled Go MuscoX and I found out that you guys have a physical store.
Really?
Yeah, there's a physical store.
And so that...
Detroit?
Yeah, that's not what I expected.
I expected you guys to be a completely online brand.
But what's up with this?
That seems like you pushed a lot of chips to the middle.
What's going on here?
So that's interesting.
So something in the algorithm is gone wrong.
So we have had a physical store.
We launched a pop-up store in suburban Detroit over the holidays.
And that was something we were really excited about.
It did well, but we did decide to close that at the end of February.
We are clearly an online retailer, but we don't have a retail store at this moment.
But let me tell you this.
I'm seeing some pictures on Google and that's a store I would walk into around November.
Maybe October.
I see Go MuscoX up top.
I see the flannel in the window.
I see some pictures in the background of people in the mountains.
I'm walking in that store.
Maybe it's interesting where this brand presents itself in a physical form.
Like you just see that image.
You instantly understand everything about it.
Whereas if I'm online, I'm trying to make a living on Instagram ads or something like
that.
It doesn't present like that.
There's a tangible nature to what you're doing and you're trying to win the battle in
a digital landscape.
That's difficult.
It is difficult.
And I think you hit on something that's super interesting and that we've found when we've
gone and done these little pop-up stores around the holidays or some festival and were invited
to attend.
And obviously the last year hasn't afforded a lot of opportunities for that.
But prior to that, we sold a lot of stuff because people got a chance to see and feel
and touch the quality of it, which is tough to know from an online photograph.
And we sold a lot of it.
That was really what prompted us to say, huh, maybe we should open a retail store because
prices are pretty low right now in terms of being able to rent out a storefront.
And so we did that now.
We're at a spot where that's something we can absolutely reconsider.
And if we were to open up a retail store, not in a pop-up capacity, where would we want
to go and where would we be?
This is another interesting, fascinating debate where it's like, well, do you go somewhere
where there's a lot of foot traffic?
Or do you go somewhere that really resonates with the brand?
And I think that's another set of really interesting questions for us to figure out.
So where are you at, Brad?
You're doing a hard thing, man.
You're making a brand that really revolves around me walking up and feeling the shirt.
That's the first thing you do when you buy a shirt is you feel it and how soft is that?
Or in this case, how thick is that?
How rugged is that?
You know, that's what you need to feel in order to close the deal.
That's what you're trying to do.
You're doing a hard thing.
So where are you at with all this, man?
I think it's important to stay the course in terms of what we're doing, right?
Because we're not flashy.
We're not sexy.
But we do really good stuff.
And over time, the truth sort of rises to the surface.
So I think on one hand, we've got to be willing to stay the course and let people
start to talk.
We are getting some good word of mouth.
It's not a very small scale relative to some of the other players that we've discussed
on this podcast.
So I think we need to be patient.
On the other hand, we need to make a decision.
We need to pick a lane for the brand and lean into it a lot further than we have.
I haven't done a great job leading lately because I've sort of been kicking the can
on this a little bit.
And it's okay in some ways because right now the spring and summer stuff is out.
It's up.
So we're not at an inflection point where we need to make an investment in warm weather
gear.
We're for sure going to continue investing the cold weather gear.
So we're doing that.
Sure.
We need to make a decision for the direction of the brand.
And we talked through a couple of them, right?
Hey, we could go leading to the animal piece.
We could lean into the cold weather outdoors.
We could pick a particular sport or two and try to really lean in there or activities.
We need to make a choice and be willing to say no to something.
That's the number one thing that's on my list when it comes to Muscocs right now.
Is it possible that you end up putting your products in shields, REI, that kind of model?
We'd love to.
This goes back to the cost structure because we are small.
The cost per unit for us to make is higher.
So we're not making a ton of money on every individual item.
You want to be in the 50 to 60 percent margin.
So meaning if you're selling something for $100, it costs you 50 is where you want to
be.
We're not quite there yet.
We're close.
But that applies too when you're talking about selling it to shields or REI.
If shields is paying you $100, you want your cost to be around 50 bucks in order to make
everything work.
We don't have room in our pricing right now to be able to do that at scale.
But for us to really be able to get to that scale where we could sell in retail as you're
proposing that, we'd have to take a whole bunch of chips going back to your analogy
destined to push even more into the center of the table.
That's scary too.
Which probably isn't worth doing until you've really got the idea crystallized.
Thanks for being honest about the fact that it isn't yet.
That's incredibly encouraging to everybody sitting in on this conversation.
Because here's the thing.
The idea isn't perfect yet by your own evaluation.
But it's pretty good and it's off to a good start.
I think a lot of people when they sit around and think about what it would take for them
to make a thing or take a risk or have a second project or whatever, they imagine this thing
has got to be completely dialed before you can ever go.
And listening to you talk, it sounds like completely dialed before you ever hit launch.
Maybe isn't very realistic.
And if you wait around forever until you got everything dialed, you're going to wait around
forever.
At some point you have to do something.
And it seems like at some point in all of this, you reached that pivot point where you
were like, all right, the idea is good enough.
Let's try it.
As some of this, we're just going to have to learn after we do it.
I mean, what would you say to somebody who's like, man, I guess I'm going to follow that
model too.
I have maybe a good enough idea to give this thing a try.
I'm going to hit go.
At what point does it make sense to hit go and take a swing at the thing?
You know, when it's time, you'll know.
I think surrounding yourself with people who are willing to give you that nudge, give you
that teeny ounce of pressure is really healthy.
But so many of us, we try to get things perfect.
One of the things that I like to say and I sure as heck didn't come up with this is
don't let perfect be the enemy of good.
When you've got something that's good, you need to go after it because, you know, in
the startup world, we say execution needs strategy for breakfast.
Strategies important.
Shoot, I used to be a strategy consultant years in the past, executing, learning from your
customers, changing, evolving, and just making sure you're continuing to improve and do things
the right way.
That's how you win.
We're trying to make things better.
But I don't think we've figured everything out.
So that's something we're trying to solve.
And it's really helpful to be able to kick this around with two really smart guys like
yourself.
So I appreciate your willingness to dive in and be good friends in that you're challenging
in poking holes.
That to me is a sign of progress.
Thank you for letting us do that, by the way.
Straight to the front door.
I think both Dustin and I agree that we thought it would be a lot more interesting and value
providing conversation.
If we did poke and jab and flip it over and take it apart on the table and think about
it, this is your baby.
You got a ton of effort in this thing.
So for you to demonstrate just the sheer social maturity to let a couple of people who are
outsiders and don't have any time in it is so easy for us to make this cavalier observation
or why didn't you do this?
Thank you for your grace and humility in giving us permission and trust to poke at that.
Thank you for being willing to spend the time on.
I know it's not always easy and you guys tackle in some of those challenges head on.
These are things we've talked about a lot of them, not all of them.
It's good to talk about.
It's great to hear your insights.
Now comes the important time is we need to start to make some tough decisions.
That's one of the things Matt and I were talking about before you got on about how much we admire
the fact that you're a doer.
You do things and you actually take risks and you're willing to try.
There are a lot of people, myself included sometimes, to be paralyzed by that fear and
like, well, I don't know, it might not work.
I'm not going to do it.
So you kind of, I don't know, you seem to zoom past that phase and actually do things.
So the last question I have from my side is just pretty blunt.
I hope that's cool.
But my question is, are you scared to fail?
Like are you scared this will fail?
And how do you deal with that?
Yes.
I'm very scared that it will will fail.
But I believe that it will be successful.
I believe that even if somehow it doesn't go the way we plan and we don't ultimately
sell these things, I will have made a connection or my team will have made connections that
will be extremely valuable to them.
I've come to believe that things don't happen in a linear way that you draw it up.
There's tremendous value in drawing up the linear path.
Right?
It's the hypothesis is super important.
It's like a financial model.
It's going to be wrong every single time, but there's still value in doing it.
My life has not been a linear journey.
And I take solace in that when we're having those dark moments, we're like, Oh, gosh,
we're our sales are.
Wow, how are we missing things as a brand?
This doesn't seem like it embodies what we want Muscox to be in those moments.
I'm lucky that I've been around starting some things.
I've seen that it's kind of these failures or these challenges that in the long run tend
to be the most valuable.
And so I'm sort of staking a claim here where I'm believing that these challenges, these
struggles are ultimately worth it.
Even if it's not the goal that we set out at the beginning to achieve.
And that makes it a lot easier for me to be honest with you is that one way or another
Muscox is going to be successful.
That doesn't mean that the brand will always exist.
It doesn't mean that we're going to sell millions of dollars of clothes.
But one way or another, it's going to make an impact on my life, some people's lives
or team's life.
And that's the part that I'm 100% convinced of.
And that's the part that makes doing Muscox really exciting to me every day.
Well, I hope you sell a lot of clothes for what that's worth.
Me too.
So thank you very much, Brad.
Really appreciate your time here, man.
This was great.
Is it okay if we maybe check back in with you at different points along the way?
Like if this journey takes a turn, is it okay?
Maybe not a whole episode, but can we maybe drop in at some point and maybe do a small
segment and just check in to see how the brand is going?
I think that'd be a lot of fun, but only if you promise to continue to be honest and
challenge what we're doing.
Yeah, deal.
Yeah, I think that'd be cool.
I'm kind of emotionally invested in this thing you're doing.
And I feel risk with you.
You're pushing these chips forward.
And now that I understand what's going on in your head, it helps me understand like,
man, this is an interesting thing.
So I'm going to check in every once in a while on Instagram or whatever you're doing.
And I'm going to see like how the brand has developed.
And I think that's going to be really fun for me.
It kind of feels like the Sims a little bit.
Like I get to see somebody building a thing or like roller coaster tycoon or something.
I get to check in on your thing and see how it's going.
Matt, does that make any sense?
It makes perfect sense.
I think it's a great idea.
Can't wait to have you guys on the journey.
We appreciate it.
It's been a couple of days since we recorded that conversation.
And I've had some more time to think about the whole Muscox brand in general, stuff that
makes sense to me, stuff I still have questions about.
But I'm going to let you go first.
What are you thinking after a couple of days?
Well, one thing that occurs to me is it's easy for me to look at someone else's brand
and be like, Oh, well, why are you doing this?
And you should be doing that.
And that's not what your brand is.
And it makes me realize that I probably have those own things with my own brand.
You know, like your work brand as well as your personal human brand, or at least that's
where my brand goes with me.
Yeah, yeah, exactly.
And so this is where I'm at with Muscox.
It seems to be centered on fall, winter, maybe early spring, like cold weather because
Muscox is like a cold weather animal in my head.
Hard core.
And so to me, to have like a summer line seems like a waste of energy.
It seems like you might not get out of it what you put into it.
And so my thought was if they were to focus on the flannels and the coats and the cold
weather stuff, but also have T-shirts just for the graphic T, like the purpose of the
T-shirt line would be to further the brand itself.
But I don't think you try to do like running gear.
What are you thinking?
I strongly agree, man.
If I want cool cold weather durable flannel type gear, I'm open to somebody new being
in the conversation.
If it looks awesome and it feels right in my hand, yeah, I will give that a go.
But if I want stuff for working out, running, playing tennis, I already have that on lockdown.
And you'd have to be pretty precise with your marketing to get me to believe that your thing
is better than the trusted products I use for working out exercise stuff.
And I cannot imagine myself putting on gear that says musk ox when I know that I'm going
to play tennis in 95 degree weather, that I'm going to go through a gallon of fluids while
I do so.
I want something that has cool in the name.
I want something that sounds like it was built for that activity, whereas musk ox just sounds
like it was built for the exact opposite of the activity.
And even if they made a really good product, you can still tell by the name they picked.
This isn't really what they care about.
Yeah, this tennis gear isn't really what they're going for.
I just would never buy it.
But the other stuff that could get into my rotation.
It's interesting how strong a brand is.
A brand kind of super seeds the product itself at times.
And I was just super thrilled that Brad would take the time to even talk to us about this
stuff.
How about that?
I don't know if I could do that that well.
If I went on somebody else's show and they're like, I would want to talk about what you
make or what you do.
We want to talk about your thought process with your brand and what about it is working
and what doesn't.
And we want to criticize it.
I mean, criticize sounds harsh, but we want to poke at it.
I don't think I could do it as well as he just did it.
Yeah, it was like next level honesty.
For me personally, I found it to be really, really valuable because I'm able to look at
his thought process and turn that around on myself and be like, oh, I'm not thinking
through what's smarter every day that the brand is like to the level that he's thinking
through Muscox.
Like, I guess I don't have a physical product that I sell.
But I think it's useful to think about what happens in someone else's mind when you say
the name of the thing you do, even if you haven't even put something in their hands.
I mean, that's a valuable exercise.
Well, it comes back to the thing we were talking about the very beginning of our conversation.
Branding is a story.
And that's why I don't remember how long ago it was, buddy.
Like four or five years ago now, you and I were talking about the idea of a personal
brand and how whether we mean to or not everyone is building a personal brand on some level
as a means of staying sane, of finding meaning and relevance and some sense of uniqueness
in a world where increasingly you can connect with everybody else on the planet.
And we all have a lot in common.
I don't think it's a coincidence at all that we're seeing more really dynamic, really unique
expressions of self that nobody has done in the past.
And I think the reason for that is we do want to occupy our own real estate as individuals.
And when you make a formal brand that you're trying to invite other people into the story,
I think it's getting more and more difficult to find that little space where the story
is unique, but not so dang weird that it's unappealing.
And I think they're on to something with the logo, with the mascot, with the name Muscox.
It's cool.
It's a niche name that should target its strength and its strength is stuff that makes you feel
like you want to be warmer than what you feel right now.
And they make really reliable stuff that does that.
You lean into that.
It works.
You venture away from that story that makes them them.
I think it might get weird.
Yeah.
And one thing I want to bring up, I don't know, this might be off topic, might not, but I
think the secret to having a good brand is for it to be general enough that everybody
is invited in, but specific enough that people want to jump on board.
And I think one thing I'm seeing brands do a lot lately that kind of goes against that
is they're getting political.
Like brands are starting to, I saw one tweet.
It's like, well, I saw the latest news, but I don't know how I feel about it yet because
I need to wait to see how my favorite mustard brand weighs in on it.
I also saw that tweet.
And I mean, a lot of times you type LOL, but very rarely do you mean LOL.
I meant LOL after reading that tweet.
Yeah.
I don't engage with anything like that.
And that's something I try to do with Smarter Every Day is I just stay a mile away from
all the political stuff.
I don't care what you as a brand, what your position is on XYZ.
I just care if you make a good garage door opener.
I just care if your wrenches are good.
You know what I mean?
Yeah.
Yeah, that really is what I want.
I know what the counterstatement is to that, which would be, well, if something's super
obviously right or wrong, it's incumbent on a brand, a company on anyone to take a stand.
But the thing is that isn't why brands exist.
I saw something at a chain Mongolian place that I like.
And the sign on the door said, our customer's safety is our number one priority.
And I was like, well, no, if it was, you'd build safety products or you would just close
your store forever and never interact with anyone.
It's not your number one priority.
It's your important priority along with, well, also we'd like to have a business and make
money and provide food that people enjoy eating and an environment that people enjoy.
But there's this feeling that you need to signal that you think the right things and
that your priorities are somehow in line with what they ought to be when the reality is that
businesses are supposed to make money.
And if they don't make money, they no longer exist.
And then there's no conversation to be had about whoever runs their Twitter accounts
opinion anyway.
At some level, I think we just need to candidly admit that if there is a brand, if there
is a company, they would like to earn dollars.
And if they don't, it's all a moot point.
Yeah.
It's just something I see brands doing.
I think it's just a waste of energy and it actually ends up alienating people from your
products.
I'm looking forward to keeping up with Muskox in the future to see exactly where they go
with a brand and what they do.
There's another step.
Once you get the product in your hand, you can feel like what the product feels like.
And that's also a part of the brand.
So I'm going to do that too.
And that's not an ad.
That's just me saying what I'm going to do.
Yeah.
And selfishly, I want to get some of their stuff so I can compare notes with what I heard
Brad say.
And I want to get some of their stuff so that now I know what to look for in terms of the
human part of the thing that went into it.
This is a part of his soul, a part of what he is nurturing is something that he wants
to win.
The better I understand how his process works and how that physically manifests as a product,
the better I can do it that the next time I take a run at building a thing.
Yeah.
Well, this is awesome.
I think we don't do this very often, but I would actually like to see what the feedback
is from other people on this because brand hits people differently.
And I would like to know what people think about this.
So all the various ways to reach out to us, I would like to know what you think about
brands and this particular brand and what you thought, what are they doing right?
What are they doing wrong?
It's a fun thought exercise.
So yeah, hit us up.
I'd love to see that.
And maybe next time we have Brad on, we'll bring a little bit of that feedback back to
him as well.
See what he thinks of it.
Oh, yeah.
That'd be cool.
Yeah.
I'll check you out in the, the patreon threads, patreon.com slash notom questions also Twitter,
all the other places.
So sweet.
Thanks for this man.
I enjoyed it.
Yeah.
Me too.
I had a lot of brains to go and I think it was really fruitful.
I had fun as well.
Yeah, man.
All right.
Have a good one.
Cool.
Catch you buddy.
